<center><span style="font-size:42px;font-family:'Sans Forgetica';">Overview</span></span></center>
Entity 444, known as '''Anonymous Illegitimates''', abbreviated as '''AIs''' or simply '''Illegitimates''' are entities that take the form of strictly deceased people, animals, or even other entities. Unlike other similar entities like [[Entity 10]], '''Illegitimates''' are passive, and they have no differences in behavior or personality from the entity that they mimic. What they are and how they exist is unknown, but a recent discovery has proven that their formation is tied to two conditions:

*The lifeform it mimics must be deceased
*Said lifeform must have intense, unresolved mourning and grief tied to it, either from one person or multiple people

'''Anonymous Illegitimates'''' existence is entirely dependent on the people that grieve over the entity they take the form of, and as a result, '''Illegitimates''' will automatically know the location of the people that grieve over them at all times and will naturally form near said people. When an '''AI''' forms, the corpse of the entity it mimics is consumed permanently. Only one '''AI''' can be formed for each deceased entity, but one person can have multiple '''Illegitimates''' if they intensely grieve more than one person.

These entities, despite not behaving any differently from the entities they mimic, possess supernatural properties. They are functionally immortal in almost every scenario, and while they can die of natural causes or be "killed," they will eventually reawaken post-mortem and regenerate all wounds the instant their corpse or wound is not under direct sight for a prolonged period. They will grow and age just as a normal person would (unless they are mimicking another supernatural entity) and can even reproduce with other entities under specific conditions. Additionally, '''AIs''' can mimic ''all'' deceased lifeforms, even those that died outside of the Backrooms. The only way to identify an '''Illegitimate''' is if there is direct confirmation or proof that the person it mimics is deceased. Otherwise, '''Illegitimates''' are fully capable of blending into society unbeknownst, and they are associated with detrimental phenomena that they unconsciously bring onto other wanderers.
<center><span style="font-size:42px;font-family:'Sans Forgetica';">Anatomy and Behavior</span></center>
'''Anonymous Illegitimates''' have varying behaviors. They have no natural behaviors; instead, they will perfectly copy the personality traits and habits of any lifeform it mimics. Anatomically, they also borrow the exact biology of the lifeform that they occupy. Fundamentally, there is no objective or physical difference between an '''Illegitimate''' and the entity it mimics. Even after decades of research, they remain ambiguous to the point that it is not far-fetched to assume they might share the same consciousness or body as the person they copy. The most glaring evidence that helped identify these as individual entities is that they will only take the form of deceased entities, even those that are widely known to be deceased. The origins behind how they form and any ulterior intentions they may have remain unknown to this day.

'''Illegitimates''' can be fully compatible with stable reproduction as long as the entity they mimic has the same species as the other entity or is capable of asexual reproduction. However, this is severely discouraged due to the severe mental hazards associated with '''AIs''' and a high risk of the offspring being exposed to said mental hazards.

However, perhaps the most notable thing about their behavior is that they aren't hostile or use their flawless impersonations to prey on wanderers. '''Illegitimates''' genuinely believe that they are the person that they mimic, even if they aren't. Attempting to contain or persecute them is mostly futile, as they will react just as a normal person would and are even vulnerable to the [[Phenomenon 35|Roth Syndrome]]. Despite this, it is still dangerous to be in constant exposure to '''Illegitimates''', as they are known to be the root of a phenomenon known as '''dulling'''. 

'''Anonymous Illegitimates''', as explained above, are immortal. They can die temporarily, but when their corpse is left unwatched for substantial time periods, they will eventually reincarnate and look just as they did before dying. There are only 2 known ways of fully erasing or killing '''AIs''':

*If any consciousness completely forgets the person or entity they mimic, '''Illegitimates''' will gradually disappear permanently. This can happen if the person grieving the entity that an '''Illegitimate''' impersonates by any means forgets said entity, or if that person dies. In the case that the person remembering the entity dies, if they had a close bond, the '''Illegitimate''' will mourn the person before then disappearing. However, '''Illegitimates''' won't die if they are still intensely grieved by any other wanderers.
*If the person grieving over the entity the '''Illegitimate''' mimics accepts that said entity is gone forever and moves on, the '''Illegitimate''' will disappear permanently. This is notoriously difficult, as the constant presence of an '''Illegitimate''' is known to make it harder for wanderers to move on and even cause said wanderers to intentionally engage with the '''Illegitimate''' regardless of it not truly being the person they grieve. This is usually only achieved through therapy or rehabilitation but is still difficult due to the '''Dulling phenomenon'''.
<center><span style="font-size:42px;font-family:'Sans Forgetica';">Anomalies</span></center>
'''Anonymous Illegitimates''' on their own are already suspected to be the result of severe anomalies. 
They are capable of perfectly copying any living creature down to every exact detail, much unlike other shapeshifting entities like [[Entity 10|skin-stealers]] that can mimic appearances, memories, and personalities but will still possess flaws tied to their fundamental anatomy or visual appearance. 
==Dulling Phenomenon==
The '''Dulling phenomenon''' is a psychological phenomenon caused by direct exposure to '''Anonymous Illegitimates'''. This phenomenon is observed as a slow, gradual decrease in the victim's ability to empathize, socialize, and retain basic morals. This creates a mentally hazardous feedback loop, as the earlier stages of the '''Dulling''' phenomenon will exacerbate the intense grief that wanderers may feel for deceased loved ones, further worsening the risks of exposure to '''Illegitimates'''. This phenomenon represents the main danger associated with '''Anonymous Illegitimates'''.

The phenomenon isn't exactly tied to physical exposure, but to constant engagement, communication, or socialization with the '''Illegitimate'''. This phenomenon can spread over to groups of people even if said people don't grieve the entity the '''Illegitimate''' mimics, but the symptoms are generally more intense in those who mourn. The level of exposure can also be increased if there is more than one '''Illegitimate''' involved.

The severity of the phenomenon increases with more exposure. It is divided into 5 stages:

{| class="article-table" style="border:2px solid white" 
! style="padding:10px 10px; border-right:1px solid white"| Stage 1
! style="padding:10px 10px"| Minimal mood changes or swings are noticeable, accompanied by a more aggravated or irritable personality. The effects are mostly manageable, although they still have impacts on the victim's social life.
|-
! style="padding:10px 10px; border-right:1px solid white"| Stage 2
! style="padding:10px 10px"| Effects become hazardous. The wanderer is more prone to chronic mental illnesses such as depression, schizophrenia, anxiety, or obsessive-compulsive disorder. These vary significantly from their natural versions, usually being more erratic and intense. This effect is significantly more noticeable on people who actively grief the Illegitimate's host.
|-
! style="padding:10px 10px; border-right:1px solid white"| Stage 3
! style="padding:10px 10px"| The wanderer becomes completely dysfunctional in normal socialization. Beyond this point, the wanderer's capability to feel empathy or basic morals is severely hindered, though still present. Any mental illnesses developed in Stage 2 peak here. The Illegitimate usually remains the only anchor in the wanderer's life, increasing rate of exposure to fatal levels. 
|-
! style="padding:10px 10px; border-right:1px solid white"| Stage 4
! style="padding:10px 10px"| Integration into society is permanently destroyed. Beyond this point, the wanderer is mostly in a chronic delirious state, and few wanderers on Stage 4 make it any longer, as their extremely damaged mind is incapable of processing danger or common survival sense. Feelings of grief continue to increase, and the wanderer is now fully stripped of their sense of empathy.  
|-
! style="padding:10px 10px; border-right:1px solid white"| Stage 5
! style="padding:10px 10px"| All mental degradation experienced by the victim beyond this point frequently turns into suicidal thoughts, and the '''Illegitimate''' and the wanderer enter a parasitic relationship. Illnesses can develop into severe chronic psychosis or sociopathy. Further degradation is still possible beyond this stage, and the only way to end the victim's suffering is a mercy kill that effectively ends the process and removes the '''Illegitimate'''. 
|}


The only way to avoid the '''Dulling''' phenomenon is identifying the '''Illegitimate''' as early as possible before it gets to bond or engage with any wanderer. The effects of the '''Dulling''' phenomenon are irreversible, and while rehabilitation is possible, it is largely ineffective.
<center><span style="font-size:42px;font-family:'Sans Forgetica';">History</span></span></center>
'''Anonymous Illegitimates''' are thought to have mostly existed amongst society in the Backrooms unnoticed for almost as long as it has existed. Only in modern times has the existence of '''Anonymous Illegitimates''' been confirmed. Previously, the only documented anomaly that was tied to '''Illegitimates''' is the '''Dulling''' phenomenon, which was previously thought to be its own, individual phenomenon, that has been documented for centuries.Tthere was a widespread surge in people witnessing the dead come back to life, but limitations in technology are what prevented any official documentation, as '''Illegitimates''' were often mistaken for skin-stealers or even hallucinations.

Anyhow, doubts have always existed regarding '''Illegitimates'''. Communities around the 1700s developed myths around these entities long before they were classified, as despite similarities with other entities, many facets showed that '''Anonymous Illegitimates''' were their own entity, according to the public. Soon, in the 1900s, the first major suspicions arose due to an influx of '''Illegitimates''' appearing on a large scale, and official research operations run by the newly established [[M.E.G.]] began around 1958. This series of operations notoriously lasted very long, only concluding in 2017. Results showed that while biologically, '''Illegitimates''' were exactly the same as a normal human, they were capable of reviving. Investigation proved that '''Illegitimates''' of recently dead Wanderers were far more frequent than others, and experiments confirmed that deaths that were kept classified or isolated from the public resulted in no '''Illegitimates''' for said person, and in other cases, they only appeared once the death of said person was made public. Additionally, constant exposure to '''Illegitimates''' during research across many decades showed that '''Illegitimates''' appeared to be the source of the widely known '''Dulling''' phenomenon. About 158 M.E.G. researchers that had been involved in the operations were diagnosed with Stage 4 of the '''Dulling''' phenomenon over the span of one century. 

In 2017, '''Anonymous Illegitimates''' were finally classified as entities. However, to this day, the mechanisms and origins behind their formation, biology, and intentions remain obscure.

{{Quote|Though we can safely confirm these entities, despite their perfect disguises, are no longer your loved ones, a festering doubt at the back of my mind has the constant fear that in some twisted way, a small part of them remains in that shell.|Russell Ford, Head Researcher of Anonymous Illegitimates in M.E.G.}}
