=<center>'''Who am I'''</center>=
<center>
I was recently informed my husband committed suicide. 


I never understood.


I wanted to, But I couldn't.


The past year had been the best days of our lives. I remember when he first disappeared.


I couldn't stop crying. But then, I arrived here.


I can't remember how or why.


But then, I saw him. 


All the pain from before faded away.


It could seem nonsensical, but in a world like this, having a loved one was a miracle.


There were times we had to run. Times we considered what it would feel like to just not be with the world anymore.



The day before he died was the best night.



After hours of walking in the endless beach, we met eachother


The memory is fuzzy now, but I remember we talked about or favorite songs from before we ended up here


We talked about what we would do if we found an exit


Sometimes, we laid on the floor without saying a word and looked at the sky


And then, we fell asleep



I woke up here, in this cellar


I remember some researchers interrogated me



I was never told why, but I answered


But I couldn't stop thinking about where he could have gone



I received the unfortunate news



That same night, he sank into the ocean on his own will



And drowned



Reportedly, they found his corpse, but I didn't want to see it


I could remember it clearly now


He had told me that he wanted to be the sea


He wanted to move with the tides and splash without a single thought


Then, he told me to sleep


Tomorrow would be a new day





I wasn't crying



I tried to, but it felt alien



I asked the researchers, "Why can't I cry?"



I don't know if it was to tell the truth or just torture



But I was told why it happened


I wanted to question it


I wanted to scream in denial and tell the researchers it's their fault


But if anything, it made sense


I remember that sometimes I struggled to recall what life felt like


But I didn't care



Is this my consequence?


Why do I still remember all their names


Why do I still remember the feel of his hand on mine



Why do I still breathe


Maybe that was the trick


The trick was I ever believed that I could feel true joy in this reality without a sacrifice


And now, he was the sacrifice






In the following hours, I was sent back to the beach


Was it cruel, or was it just so I could have some sense of peace?


I wanted to do the same thing he did, but I couldn't


Even if I tried


I can't remember if it was minutes, hours, weeks, or months



How many times my blood spilled over the floor, those memories all came to me


But I still denied it



Denied that this was real


I still feel like I am the same one from that night


What truly made him, me, or anyone a person?


Their identity? Their body? Their soul?


I don't know


I don't think I ever will
</center>
---------------------------
'''Jane Marie Joseph''' was a young woman that passed away in a fatal car accident in [[The Frontrooms]]. This happened shortly before her husband, **** ***** ***, reportedly noclipped into the Backrooms, estimated to be somewhere around '''1989'''. A case of Entity 444 was quick to form, assuming the identity of '''Jane'''. **** and '''Jane''' remained in contact for over one year, and **** quickly developed a severe case of the '''Dulling''' phenomenon. However, he managed to seemingly hide the illness for over one year before, in 2002, suffering from Stage 5, took his own life in [[Level 100]] by intentionally drowning himself. The '''Illegitimate''' identified as '''Jane''' was then found wandering in [[Level 102]] and was swiftly taken to a M.E.G. base for research. Seemingly, one of the scientists identified her as an '''Anonymous Illegitimate''' during interrogation, leading to her becoming unstable.

Once research concluded, she was dropped off at a temporally controlled area within [[Level 100]], where she was expected to promptly disappear, given her host had passed away. Hours after, while inspecting for any remains, an abandoned notepad was found belonging to her and was recovered for research. Said notepad was identified to be a diary, and while there are many entries that further helped document '''Illegitimates''', the transcript above is specifically the final entry, presumably written moments before the '''Illegitimate''''s passing. 
