<div style="background: #000000; border: 3px solid #ffffff; border-radius: 5px; padding: 26px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; box-shadow: 0.2px 2.5px 2px rgb(255, 255, 255); margin: 5px 10px; color: #ffffff; margin">
='''Final Report, Entity 444'''=
'''December 24, 2016'''<br>
'''Documented by Dr. Russell Ford, [[M.E.G.]]'''
--------------------------
After decades of dedicating my life to investigating these entities, it is time I finally achieve a proper consensus.<br>
I could continue my research on '''Entity 444''', but even after trying my absolute best to minimize my contact with these entities, I have constantly been advised that continuing this operation risks me potentially developing a lethal case of [[Phenomenon 35]], and once documentation and formal publishing of this entity to [[The Database]] is finalized, I will be promptly retiring from [[M.E.G.]]. This is my final report on '''Entity 444, Anonymous Illegitimates'''.

'''Entity 444''' is a sapient entity of unknown origin and the only one that we have observed in the Backrooms fully capable of perfectly mimicking and copying the exact structure and anatomy of any human or entity. While true confirmation remains vague, we have more than enough evidence to demonstrate these are '''''not''''' human by all means, and that no matter how similar they may look to your loved ones, you know deep inside that they are gone.

I made it my whole life to make sure that nobody has to fall victim to one of these entities. It has been painful conducting my investigations. I have lost all my motivation to continue my efforts, and I only barely hold onto sanity by an extensive amount of sedatives I must take. I remember it must have been the late 1950s. My dog, Yachi, appeared in the Backrooms. It was when I was only in my 20s, yet I knew it couldn't be true. That either it was a fabricated lie generated by the Backrooms or a very cruel entity.

[[File:Cuteyachi.png|300px|center|link= ]] 

I sent it to be tested, unknowingly exposing many people to the Dulling phenomenon. Everything was similar. He even remembered the tricks I made it learn before I arrived here. I knew it couldn't be some sort of skin-stealer because I know that Yachi never entered the Backrooms, nor did I ever wish he had. I had "Yachi" be killed over and over. I heard its whines. They tried what they could. Shock him to death, poison him, or burn him. And every time I thought it was over, he was there. Panting like we had just taken a walk. I couldn't pet him. I wanted to. Because I knew that even if it wasn't true, I would never be able to experience it again. 

Yet, my decisions turned out to be good. Because I mostly avoided being near Yachi, I had only minimal exposure to the Dulling phenomenon. That allowed me to keep the mental fortitude that the next decades of my life would require. The hardest part was moving on. In the end, Yachi was never killed off. We kept it contained. The voice in my mind told me that going to its cellar to just see him for a few seconds would be enough. But I knew I couldn't. Eventually, one day, he disappeared. Gone.

I asked [[M.E.G.]]. They told me this is one of the first times they have directly observed this "anomaly" in action. Before arriving in the Backrooms, I was deeply into the paranormal. I spent a lot of time making and writing theories on urban legends and mythology. But I never could actually prove the existence of the paranormal. But part of the fun of it was the mystery of whether it was real or not. Seeing it firsthand when I first arrived here broke something in me. And the recent incident had only made it worse.

One year after, I joined M.E.G. I made it my mission that in the distant future of this realm, nobody would have to suffer what I did and, if not, at least minimize it. It is an ambitious goal, really. And a stupid one at the same time. Trying to be a hero in this place is mostly futile. You won't be remembered for your changes. Everyone is too lost, too confused to think about. Few even make it through the first 5 levels. But I wasn't trying to be a hero. I was trying to give myself a purpose that doesn't feel degrading in this world. And even that brought me even lower than I was before.

But by the time I had made progress in my studies, it was already too late to turn back. The operation had gone from a localized incident to one of the longest-running investigations M.E.G. had ever conducted, at least in its time. I noticed patterns. Despite my endless complaints and ethical concerns, the operation demanded we observe a case of how Wanderers and '''Entity 444''' interact. We noticed patterns in how Wanderers behaved. How they slowly stopped caring about anything but whoever '''Entity 444''' was masquerading as. The aftermath was consistent, too. The wanderer either turned into a [[Phenomenon 35|wretch]], went missing, or had to be executed. The '''AI''' would remain there for a while, but when, just like Yachi, it would disappear. 

We also noticed that Yachi wasn't entirely a unique case. We interrogated the wanderers affected by '''Entity 444''', and roughly 96% of them confirmed the person that the '''Entity 444''' mimicked had previously died. The other 4% were unique cases in which the person that the '''Illegitimate''' was mimicking had died in the Frontrooms without the wanderer being able to see it prior to entering the Backrooms. Despite this odd minority, we came to the conclusion that '''Entity 444''' could only copy deceased lifeforms.

This all didn't happen in a few hours, days, or weeks. Reaching this conclusion alone took us 6 years. It might seem ridiculous for our modern standards, but back then it was very hard to find any cases of '''Entity 444''', and finding an affected wanderer that was sane enough to interrogate was even harder. Most of the time we spent was debating and confirming if these entities were anomalies, phenomena, real, or, most chillingly, the real people they 'impersonate.' The other time was spent finding and researching these entities and developing a formal classification of the Dulling phenomenon.

It was 2001. Finally, the hardest thing we had to investigate was their actual formation and origin. The first few cases and Yachi helped us know these entities are seemingly immortal, but up to this point, we never knew why Yachi, and so many other '''Illegitimates''', had suddenly disappeared. In many cases, we noted that '''Entity 444''' only disappeared only when the wanderer it was with died. We tried making a conclusion based off that, but I knew it couldn't be true. Yachi disappeared, and I was still alive. Alive to see it all. So there must have been another precedent behind how '''Entity 444''' truly dies and how it is born. So I began the final stages of the operation.

Since we knew '''Illegitimates''' could only mimic deceased people, we tried having volunteers offer their lives and see if any '''Illegitimates''' would spawn. One of the volunteers was a frail, old wanderer who claimed he had lived his life lonely, with nobody he found remarkable. He wanted it all to end. When he died, no '''Illegitimate''' was formed that we could observe. Then what could it be? What truly was the reason behind why these entities spawned? 

[[File:Artworks-000203569231-kqu128-t500x500.jpg|300px|center|link= ]]

For a moment, we reached a roadblock. I took some time to look back on what I had done and why I had done it. The motivation, the push I had, was gone. I no longer kept researching these entities to help others. It had all been watered down to just me doing my job. I didn't care about the people that were affected anymore by these entities. It came to me. I had ''killed'' people for this operation. I might not see it, but how many of these monsters would it have spawned? How many people would lose their identities to them? 

Fuck it all. I had gotten old. I had burnt myself out for this positive goal, and in the end it was still bleak. Like I had made no change. Like I had just wasted most of my life dedicating myself to a cause that was ultimately meaningless. An artificial resolve. 

My colleagues feared the worst. They suggested I take a check with my assigned therapist. 

I was diagnosed with Stage 3 of the Dulling phenomenon.

[[File:10-108571 transparent-cracks-screen-cracked-phone-screen-transparent-1320816513.png|300px|center|link= ]]

It brought to me a very important question. Can these entities feel emotion? They drain it so much. Feed off loss. But is their perfect mimicking just a facade? A shell, or a blank canvas? I remembered the recent case of a woman who had deeply mourned the death of her spouse, an interview recorded by my team. That woman was an '''Illegitimate'''. It made me sick to the stomach. So the very entities that cause us grief and sorrow have the capacity to, in their last moments, mourn their victims? 

I faced the reality that in some way, these entities truly did have emotion. They thought they were themselves. I suggested it to the team. They said it was insane, but at that point, what was sane and insane? What line divided them? It made it into the documentation still. I didn't complain. I stayed silent. More than I ever did in this operation. I was the lead, but I had reasonably been gradually sidelined by the rest of my colleagues after I was diagnosed with the Dulling phenomenon. I could understand their thinking. But why were they so surprised? I have been on the frontline facing these pests for decades, and they think I'll come out unscathed?

Grief. Mourning. Loss.

I found it. How could I have not thought of it?

That must be the true meaning behind these entities. 

That is why that lonely man never had an Illegitimate, but Yachi did. Nobody ever cared about that man. But after losing Yachi, I was in grief. I remember back when I was in Earth, I'd whistle to his ghost in my house and throw his favorite toy for him to fetch. That entity I had seen perfectly copying him was the embodiment of that grief. The culmination of my wish for a better life coming to haunt me even in another dimension.


We were finishing, but then [[Phenomenon 12|the flicker]] came around. It definitely slowed down progress, and my colleagues were in panic. Some did not make it to see this project ever end. 

Now, I am writing this. I will admit, the conclusion I made before was kind of rushed, but with how long this project had lasted, with how complicated everything had gotten over here with the whole blackout, and how much money this had cost to run, nobody had any better answers than mine. Nothing unexpected, really. I know this will likely be put on the page when it is fully documented, but I want everyone that's reading this to know that whatever goal you have, whatever life you wish for in this realm, think about it. In all honesty, I resent you. I've said everything I have to say, yet it can't convey what I felt. How pale it all is, how little I care. So you'll read all of this, and you will now know how to "survive" this entity. It doesn't matter how you do it; if you succeed or fail, that is all that has ever mattered. That is what I should have been. 

''Yachi''. Even now, I still miss him. He's maybe the only thing I ever cared about. Yet, is even that feeling real? Are the effects of me being with his fake still prevalent today? Or have I truly gone beyond repair?


If you see Entity 444, don't run from it or try to report it to an organization. Whoever you deeply miss, they are gone. That is all you have to know. What you do with that information I couldn't care less about.
